---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import Nav from "../components/Nav.astro";
import TimeMachine from "../components/TimeMachine.astro";

const REPO = "https://github.com/0x-copilot-dev/0x-copilot";
const DISCORD = "https://discord.com/invite/NhCv7zDkmX";
const X = "https://x.com/Copilot0x";

// The twelve real destinations, read off the running app's rail.
const SURFACES = [
  ["home", "Your day: triage + live activity"],
  ["chats", "Conversations and streamed runs"],
  ["inbox", "Approvals and anything waiting on you"],
  ["todos", "Tasks, recurring series, bulk actions"],
  ["projects", "Scoped work, members, templates"],
  ["library", "Files and datasets, indexed"],
  ["agents", "Install and run subagents"],
  ["tools", "What it can call — and every call it made"],
  ["connectors", "MCP servers, OAuth, per-chat scope"],
  ["team", "Shared work across your org"],
  ["memory", "What it learned, and what it keeps"],
  ["routines", "Work that runs on a schedule"],
];
---

<Base
  title="0xCopilot — the agent that does the work, and shows it"
  description="Agentic AI got built for engineers. 0xCopilot brings it to everyone else — an agent that does multi-step work across your apps and shows every step. Local, BYOK, open source."
>
  <Nav />

  <!-- ============================ HERO ============================ -->
  <header class="hero">
    <div class="hero-bg"></div>
    <div class="hero-grid"></div>
    <div class="wrap">
      <span class="pill"><span class="dot pulse"></span> Pre-launch · building in the open</span>
      <h1>The agent that does the work <em>— and shows it.</em></h1>
      <p class="sub">
        Cursor, Codex and Claude Code built real agents — for people who write
        code. <b>0xCopilot brings that to everyone else.</b> It takes on
        multi-step work across your files and the apps you already use, and
        streams every step as it happens. <b>Rewind any run. Stop it before it
        lands.</b> Your machine, your key, your model.
      </p>
      <div class="cta-row">
        <a class="btn pri" href="#work">See how it runs</a>
        <a class="btn ghost" href={REPO} rel="noopener">Read the source ↗</a>
        <a class="btn ghost" href={DISCORD} rel="noopener">Join the Discord ↗</a>
      </div>
      <div class="trust">
        <b>OpenAI · Anthropic · Google — your key</b>
        <span class="s"></span>
        <b>Open source</b>
        <span class="s"></span>
        <span>Launching via Virtuals on Robinhood Chain</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </header>

  <!-- ============================ DEMO ============================ -->
  <section class="band">
    <div class="wrap"><TimeMachine /></div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============================ THE GAP ============================ -->
  <section class="sec" id="what">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="kick">The gap</p>
      <h2 class="head-wide">Agentic AI got built for engineers.</h2>
      <p class="lede">
        The breakthroughs of the last two years are extraordinary — and nearly
        every one is pointed at a repo. The people who run <b>treasury,
        community, governance and growth</b> got a chat box and a copy button.
        0xCopilot is the agent for that work: it opens your sheets, your
        multisig, your threads and your Discord, and does the multi-step thing
        end to end — where you can watch it, rewind it, and stop it.
      </p>
      <div class="compare">
        <div class="cc">
          <p class="lab">Built for the repo</p>
          <div class="chips">
            <span class="chip">Cursor</span>
            <span class="chip">Codex</span>
            <span class="chip">Claude Code</span>
            <span class="chip">Rovo</span>
            <span class="chip">Cowork</span>
          </div>
          <p>Real agents, real multi-step work — pointed almost entirely at source code.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="cc open">
          <p class="lab">Built for the rest of the org</p>
          <div class="chips">
            <span class="role">Treasury</span>
            <span class="role">Community</span>
            <span class="role">Governance</span>
            <span class="role">Growth</span>
            <span class="role">Ops</span>
            <span class="role">Comms</span>
          </div>
          <div class="win">0x<span class="sky">Copilot</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============================ THE WEDGE ============================ -->
  <section class="sec" id="work">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="kick">The wedge</p>
      <h2 class="head-wide">
        An agent that does the work is the easy part. One whose work you can
        check is the point.
      </h2>
      <p class="lede">
        0xCopilot makes every run a <b>durable, ordered log of typed events</b> —
        not a black box that emits a summary. That's the whole demo above: you
        don't get a spinner, you watch the work happen and scrub back through it.
      </p>
      <div class="cards">
        <div class="card">
          <h3><span class="g sky"></span>Watch</h3>
          <p>Every step is a typed event, streamed live — plans, tool calls, results — not a summary at the end.</p>
          <span class="api">GET /v1/agent/runs/:id/stream</span>
          <div class="mock">
            <div class="ev"><span class="t">12:04:01</span><span class="n">run.started</span></div>
            <div class="ev ok"><span class="t">12:04:03</span><span class="n">sheet.read</span><span class="arg">tokenomics.xlsx</span></div>
            <div class="ev ok"><span class="t">12:04:06</span><span class="n">safe.tx.staged</span><span class="arg">3,100 → nova.eth</span></div>
            <div class="ev"><span class="t">12:04:09</span><span class="n">x.thread.draft</span><span class="arg">64%</span><span class="cur"></span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3><span class="g jade"></span>Rewind</h3>
          <p>Events persist with a monotonic sequence number per run. Replay from any point, or reconnect and resume where you dropped.</p>
          <span class="api">?after_sequence=N</span>
          <div class="mock">
            <div class="tlm"><div class="fill"></div><div class="bead" style="left:14%"></div><div class="bead" style="left:38%"></div><div class="bead" style="left:62%"></div><div class="head"></div></div>
            <div class="seqline"><span>seq 0</span><span>seq 128 · now</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3><span class="g amber"></span>Steer</h3>
          <p>Anything that touches the real world pauses and waits for your go-ahead. Approve it, redirect it, or stop the run mid-flight.</p>
          <span class="api">run.waiting_for_permission</span>
          <div class="mock">
            <div class="approve">
              <div class="q">Send <span class="hl">3,100 USDC</span> to nova.eth?</div>
              <div class="abtns"><span class="ab go">Approve</span><span class="ab">Redirect</span><span class="ab stop">Stop</span></div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============================ SURFACES ============================ -->
  <section class="sec">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="kick">Not a chatbot</p>
      <h2 class="head-wide">Twelve surfaces, not one text box.</h2>
      <p class="lede">
        Chat is the right rail, not the whole product. The work lands on real
        surfaces you can open, filter and act on — and the agent works the same
        surfaces you do.
      </p>
      <div class="surf">
        {
          SURFACES.map(([name, what]) => (
            <div class="tile">
              <div class="nm">{name}</div>
              <div class="ds">{what}</div>
            </div>
          ))
        }
      </div>
      <div class="shot" style="height:auto;margin-top:44px">
        <img src="./media/welcome.png" alt="The real 0xCopilot app — a new chat offering to draft a launch announcement, summarize Slack, find brand guidelines, or compare a competitor." style="position:static;height:auto" />
      </div>
      <p class="cap"><b>The real app, today — not a mockup. The demo up top is the same product, dressed for a launch-week scenario.</b></p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============================ YOURS ============================ -->
  <section class="sec" id="local">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="kick">Yours</p>
      <div class="two">
        <div>
          <h2>Your machine. Your key. Your model.</h2>
          <p class="lede">
            0xCopilot runs locally. Bring your own API key — it talks to OpenAI,
            Anthropic or Google, and you pay your provider directly. No seat
            license, no subscription tier, no middleman between you and the model
            you chose.
          </p>
          <div class="providers">
            <span class="prov">OpenAI</span>
            <span class="prov">Anthropic</span>
            <span class="prov">Google</span>
            <span class="prov">Local model</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="callouts">
          <div class="callout">
            <div class="ct">Keys never touch a request body</div>
            <div class="cp">Provider keys live in your own environment — enforced in the codebase, not promised here.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="callout">
            <div class="ct">Connectors use real OAuth</div>
            <div class="cp">Tokens sit in a <code>vault</code> you run.</div>
          </div>
          <div class="callout">
            <div class="ct">Point it at a local model</div>
            <div class="cp">Then nothing leaves your machine at all.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============================ RUN IT ============================ -->
  <section class="sec">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="kick">Run it</p>
      <h2>One command, on your hardware.</h2>
      <p class="lede">
        Today 0xCopilot runs as a local stack you bring up with Docker and open
        in your browser at <b>127.0.0.1:8080</b>. The runtime, the stores and the
        event log all stay on your machine.
      </p>
      <div class="codewrap">
        <div class="codebar"><span class="tl-dot r"></span><span class="tl-dot y"></span><span class="tl-dot g"></span><span class="fn">~/0xcopilot</span></div>
        <pre><code><span class="c"># bring up the local stack</span>
<span class="p">$</span> OPENAI_API_KEY=$OPENAI_API_KEY make docker-dev

<span class="c"># open it</span>
<span class="p">$</span> open http://127.0.0.1:8080

<span class="c"># stop it — nothing left running, nothing left behind</span>
<span class="p">$</span> make docker-dev-down</code></pre>
      </div>
      <p class="note">
        <b>Native macOS and Windows apps are in design and not shipped yet.</b>
        Until they land, the local stack is the product — and it's the same code
        you'll read on GitHub.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============================ TOKEN ============================ -->
  <section class="sec tok">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="kick">The token</p>
      <h2>The app is the product.</h2>
      <p class="lede">
        0xCopilot is launching a token via Virtuals Protocol on Robinhood Chain.
        Half the supply goes to the market on a fair launch, a quarter to the
        people who build it, and a quarter to protocol-run capital formation —
        released only as the market verifies progress.
      </p>
      <div class="bar">
        <div class="seg mkt">50%&nbsp; Fair launch</div>
        <div class="seg bld">25%&nbsp; ESOP</div>
        <div class="seg pro">25%&nbsp; ACF</div>
      </div>
      <div class="tlegend">
        <div class="tl-item">
          <div class="lt"><span class="sw mkt"></span>Market — fair launch</div>
          <p>Half the supply, tradable from the first block. No lock, no pre-buy.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="tl-item">
          <div class="lt"><span class="sw bld"></span>Builders — ESOP</div>
          <p>Reserved for the people who ship the product, on a protocol lock + grant vesting.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="tl-item">
          <div class="lt"><span class="sw pro"></span>Capital formation</div>
          <p>Protocol-run, tied to valuation. No discretionary insider selling.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="cta-row">
        <a class="btn pri" href="./token.html">See the full tokenomics</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============================ FAQ ============================ -->
  <section class="sec">
    <div class="wrap">
      <p class="kick">Answers</p>
      <h2>The questions that decide trust.</h2>
      <div class="faq">
        <div class="qa">
          <div class="q">Can it do things without asking me?</div>
          <div class="a">That's your call, per run. Steps that touch the real world can pause for explicit approval before they execute — the run parks in <b>waiting_for_permission</b> until you answer, and you can stop it at any point. Permission policy is configuration; read the source and set it before you point this at anything that matters.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="qa">
          <div class="q">Where do my API keys live?</div>
          <div class="a">In your own environment file, on your machine. Provider keys are never accepted in a run request body — <b>enforced in code</b>. OAuth tokens for connectors go into a token vault running in your stack.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="qa">
          <div class="q">Is any of this cloud-dependent?</div>
          <div class="a">The stack runs on your hardware. The one thing that leaves is what you'd expect: your prompts and context go to whichever provider's key you supplied. Point it at a local model and nothing leaves at all.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="qa">
          <div class="q">What actually works today?</div>
          <div class="a">The runtime, streaming with replay and resume, approvals, MCP connectors with OAuth, skills, memory, the library index, and the twelve surfaces above. <b>Not shipped: the native desktop apps.</b> We'd rather say that here than let you find out after a download.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============================ FOOTER ============================ -->
  <footer>
    <div class="wrap">
      <div class="frow">
        <span class="wm" style="font-size:22px">0x<b>Copilot</b></span>
        <div class="flinks">
          <a href="./token.html">Tokenomics</a>
          <a href={REPO} rel="noopener">GitHub ↗</a>
          <a href={DISCORD} rel="noopener">Discord ↗</a>
          <a href={X} rel="noopener">@Copilot0x ↗</a>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="foot-b">
        <span>© 2026 0xCopilot · Ask · Steer · Ship</span>
        <span class="ass">Nothing on this site is financial advice or an offer of securities.</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </footer>
</Base>
